			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Anyone boxing a Bard and Cleric?<a name="69993"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Nov 19 04 8:45 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I have also 2boxed a bard and a shammy for about 2 months now using my roomate's 63 shammy. The biggest difference between boxing a shammy and a cleric (as far as boxing mechanics go) is the fact that you have to get used to using canni comfortably. Another major difference is that shammy slows draw major aggro, and this can put you in a pinch if you get resisted a lot. Make sure to resist debuff the mobs otw in, it's also a good idea to use your highest Disease based Chant before bringing it back to camp because the extra disease debuff can really help shammys land thier slows, while at the same time generating at least a little bit more aggro for you. Shammy buffs are awesome but you will find yourself needing virt as well, there's really no way around it. A very helpful difference between the 2 combos is dps, you might not think it's that much but it adds up and it can really make a difference. Make sure to get some affliction effieciency and burning affliction gear for the shammy, dots are a seriously underrated source of solid dps. Shammy pets can off tank fully slowed mobs if needed but it does tend to make things a bit more hectic for the person boxing. 
<br />
   I played around with boxing a druid but he was only lvl 55 when my bard was 58, the combo really didnt work that well, but I'd imagine it would have been easier if the druid had been 58+ (druid CH). 
<br />

<br />
Anyways hope this info helps. 
<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
